SIMPLE: one
RECORDS: 6

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: -one
<hw>-one</hw> <pr>(⟦omac⟧n)</pr>. <ety>[From Gr. <grk>-w`nh</grk>,
signifying, female descendant.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A suffix
indicating that the substance, in the name of which it appears, is a
<isa>ketone</isa>; <as>as, acet<ex>one</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>-one</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: -one
<hw>-one</hw> <pos>suff.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A termination
indicating that the hydrocarbon to the name of which it is affixed
belongs to the <xex>fourth series of hydrocarbons</xex>, or the
<xex>third series of unsaturated hydrocarbons</xex>; as,
non<xex>one</xex>.</def> <mark>[archaic]</mark> ⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>One</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: One
<hw>One</hw> <pr>(w⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>one</ets>,
<ets>on</ets>, <ets>an</ets>, AS. <ets>⟦amac⟧n</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>een</ets>, OS. <ets>⟦emac⟧n</ets>, OFries. <ets>⟦emac⟧n</ets>,
<ets>⟦amac⟧n</ets>, G. <ets>ein</ets>, Dan. <ets>een</ets>, Sw.
<ets>en</ets>, Icel. <ets>einn</ets>, Goth. <ets>ains</ets>, W.
<ets>un</ets>, Ir. & Gael. <ets>aon</ets>, L. <ets>unus</ets>, earlier
<ets>oinos</ets>, <ets>oenos</ets>, Gr. <grk>o'i`nh</grk> the ace on
dice; cf. Skr. <ets>⟦emac⟧ka</ets>. The same word as the indefinite
article <ets>a</ets>, <ets>an</ets>. ⟦root⟧ 299. Cf. 2d <er>A</er>, 1st
<er>An</er>, <er>Alone</er>, <er>Anon</er>, <er>Any</er>, <er>None</er>,
<er>Nonce</er>, <er>Only</er>, <er>Onion</er>, <er>Unit</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Being a single unit, or entire being or thing, and no
more; not multifold; single; individual.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The dream of Pharaoh is <qex>one</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. xli.
25.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O that we now had here⟦br⟧
But <qex>one</qex> ten thousand of those men in England.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Denoting a person or thing conceived or spoken of
indefinitely; a certain. ⟦ldquo⟧I am the sister of <xex>one</xex>
Claudio⟦rdquo⟧ [<au>Shak.</au>], that is, of a certain man named
Claudio.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Pointing out a contrast, or denoting a particular
thing or person different from some other specified; -- used as a
correlative adjective, with or without <xex>the</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From the <qex>one</qex> side of heaven unto the other.</q>
<rj><qau>Deut. iv. 32.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Closely bound together; undivided; united;
constituting a whole.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The church is therefore <qex>one</qex>, though the members may be
many.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Pearson</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Single in kind; the same; a common.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>One</qex> plague was on you all, and on your lords.</q>
<rj><qau>1 Sam. vi. 4.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Single; unmarried.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men may counsel a woman to be <qex>one</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>One</xex> is often used in forming compound words,
the meaning of which is obvious; as, <xex>one</xex>-armed,
<xex>one</xex>-celled, <xex>one</xex>-eyed, <xex>one</xex>-handed,
<xex>one</xex>-hearted, <xex>one</xex>-horned, <xex>one</xex>-idead,
<xex>one</xex>-leaved, <xex>one</xex>-masted, <xex>one</xex>-ribbed,
<xex>one</xex>-story, <xex>one</xex>-syllable, <xex>one</xex>-stringed,
<xex>one</xex>-winged, etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>All one</b></col>, <cd>of the same or equal nature, or
consequence; all the same; <as>as, he says that it is <ex>all one</ex>
what course you take.</as></cd> <au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>One
day</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>On a certain day, not definitely
specified, referring to time past.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>One day</qex> when Phoebe fair,⟦br⟧
With all her band, was following the chase.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <cd>Referring to future time: At some uncertain day or
period in the future; some day.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Well, I will marry <qex>one day</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>One</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: One
<hw>One</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A single unit; <as>as,
<ex>one</ex> is the base of all numbers</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A symbol representing a unit, as 1, or i.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A single person or thing.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The shining
<xex>ones</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Bunyan.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧Hence, with your little
<xex>ones</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He will hate the <qex>one</qex>, and love the other.</q>
<rj><qau>Matt. vi. 24.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That we may sit, <qex>one</qex> on thy right hand, and the other
on thy left hand, in thy glory.</q> <rj><qau>Mark x. 37.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>After one</b></col>, <cd>after one fashion; alike.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Chaucer.</au> -- <col><b>At one</b></col>,
<cd>in agreement or concord. See <er>At one</er>, in the Vocab.</cd> --
<col><b>Ever in one</b></col>, <cd>continually; perpetually;
always.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Chaucer.</au> -- <col><b>In
one</b></col>, <cd>in union; in a single whole.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>One and one</b></col>, <col><b>One by
one</b></col></mcol>, <cd>singly; one at a time; one after another.</cd>
⟦ldquo⟧Raising <xex>one by one</xex> the suppliant crew.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Dryden.</au> -- <col><b>one on one</b></col> <cd>contesting an
opponent individually; -- in a contest.</cd> -- <col><b>go one on
one</b></col>, <cd>to contest one opponent by oneself; -- in a game,
esp. basketball.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1003 --></p>

<p><ent>One</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: One
<hw>One</hw> <pr>(w⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>indef. pron.</pos> <def>Any
person, indefinitely; a person or body; <as>as, what <ex>one</ex> would
have well done, <ex>one</ex> should do <ex>one's</ex>
self</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It was well worth <qex>one's</qex> while.</q>
<rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Against this sort of condemnation <qex>one</qex> must steel
<qex>one's</qex> self as <qex>one</qex> best can.</q> <rj><qau>G.
Eliot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<note><p><xex>One</xex> is often used with <xex>some</xex>,
<xex>any</xex>, <xex>no</xex>, <xex>each</xex>, <xex>every</xex>,
<xex>such</xex>, <xex>a</xex>, <xex>many a</xex>, <xex>another</xex>,
<xex>the other</xex>, etc. It is sometimes joined with
<xex>another</xex>, to denote a reciprocal relation.⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When any <qex>one</qex> heareth the word.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. xiii.
19.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She knew every <qex>one</qex> who was any <qex>one</qex> in the
land of Bohemia.</q> <rj><qau>Compton Reade.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Peloponnesians and the Athenians fought against <qex>one
another</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Jowett (Thucyd. ).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The gentry received <qex>one another</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Thackeray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></note>

<p><ent>One</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: One
<hw>One</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cause to become one; to gather
into a single whole; to unite; to assimilate.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The rich folk that embraced and <qex>oned</qex> all their heart to
treasure of the world.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Oneberry</ent>⟦br⟧
